```c++
class Solution {
public:
    string removeOccurrences(string s, string part) {
        while (s.find(part) != string::npos) {
            s.erase(s.find(part), part.length());
        }
        return s;
    }
};
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(N*M)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution iteratively searches for the substring `part` within `s`. Upon finding a match, it removes the occurrence using `erase`. This process continues until no more occurrences are found. The primary approach is a brute-force search, which can be inefficient for large strings.  The algorithm's time complexity is O(N*M) due to the repeated string searching, where N is the length of `s` and M is the length of `part`. The space complexity is O(1) as it modifies the string in-place.

